          "body": "With hope declared, David petitions. The petitions are layered and honest. First, 'deliver me from all my transgressions' (v. 8) — an acknowledgment that the suffering has a moral dimension, that God's discipline is not arbitrary. Then, 'remove Your plague from me' (v. 10) — the same God whose discipline is acknowledged is asked to lift the affliction. Both requests coexist: David is not claiming innocence, nor is he accepting permanent punishment. Verse 11 is the psalm's most theologically mature line: 'With reproofs You chasten a man for iniquity; You consume as a moth what is precious to him.' The moth-image is arresting — moths destroy silently, invisibly, over time, from the inside of the garment. Divine discipline works that way: quietly consuming what the disciplined person treasures most. David understands this, names it, and still prays for relief. That combination — understanding the discipline and still asking for mercy — is the posture of a mature sufferer, not a rebellious one. The closing appeal (vv. 12-13) grounds itself in covenant status: 'I am a stranger with You, a sojourner like all my fathers.' The legal argument is elegant — in Israel's law, the stranger is entitled to hospitality and protection (Lev. 19:33-34). David claims that status before God and asks for it to be honored: hear, give ear, do not be silent at my tears."
